    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>As per this page: <a href=\"https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/tzdata-versions-138805.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/tzdata-versions-138805.html</a></p>\n\n<p>Brazil no longer observes DST since:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>13.0.1</li>\n<li>11.0.5</li>\n<li>8u231</li>\n<li>7u241</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>while your Java version is <code>1.8.0_221</code> which does not include that change.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 322981,
      "reputation" : 346727,
      "user_id" : 642706,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 58,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/ZWEI3.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Basil Bourque",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/642706/basil-bourque"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1763692283,
    "creation_date" : 1763692283,
    "answer_id" : 79826084,
    "question_id" : 60328312,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/60328767/642706\">Answer by Eng.Fouad</a> is correct. You must keep the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tz_database\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><em>tzdata</em></a> up-to-date in your Java implementation (JDK/JRE). And remember to update the copy of <em>tzdata</em> in your host OS, and in other subsystems like database servers such as Postgres, containers such as Podman/Docker, etc.</p>\n<p>I can add more thoughts</p>\n<h2><code>LocalDateTime</code> is the wrong class</h2>\n<p>Never use <code>LocalDateTime</code> class when trying to represent a moment. That class represents only a date with time-of-day but lacks the context of time zone. So the value is inherently ambiguous as date and time vary around the globe by time zone.</p>\n<p>Tracking a moment as a <code>LocalDateTime</code>, without a time zone (or offset), is like a price without a currency (USD, EUR, CAD, JPY, etc.)… ambiguous to the point of being useless.</p>\n<h2>Moment</h2>\n<p>To represent a moment, use these classes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>java.time.Instant</code></li>\n<li><code>java.time.OffsetDateTime</code></li>\n<li><code>java.time.ZonedDateTime</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Understand that an offset is merely a number of hours-minutes-seconds ahead/behind the temporal meridian of UTC. A time zone is much more. A time zone is a named history of the changes to offset used by the people of a particular region, as determined by their politicians.</p>\n<h3>UTC</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I am changing all dates in the system to save in utc</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>To get represent a moment as it appears in UTC (an offset of zero), use <code>java.time.Instant</code>.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>Instant instant = myLocalDateTime.atOffset( ZoneOffset.UTC ).toInstant() ;\n</code></pre>\n<h3>Zoned</h3>\n<p>To present that moment as seen by someone interested in Brazil time, apply a <code>ZoneId</code> to produce a <code>ZonedDateTime</code> object.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>ZoneId z = ZoneId.of( &quot;America/Sao_Paulo&quot; ) ;\nZonedDateTime zdt = instant.atZone( z ) ;\n</code></pre>\n<p>From there use <code>DateTimeFormatter</code> to produce automatically localized text.</p>\n"
  } ],
